post_text:
Happy 7th week of distance learning! Can you believe it's been 7 weeks? (That's counting spring break.)

For the past 5 weeks, the spring sport athletes have been doing character development lessons as a way to stay engaged with teammates and coaches. This week's topic is Expectation vs Reality - it's very fitting for our current situation. This is a great message, not just for athletes, but for all of us: parents, students, teachers, community - everyone living through this time of not-knowing.

There's a short video - about 9 minutes - and then some written words to think about throughout the week. Have a look if you have the time and have a happy Thursday!

https://pagosaathletics.com/siteRepository/454/userfiles/2Words-Week-5-GP.pdf

https://vimeo.com/398894089/6030690a67

text:
Happy 7th week of distance learning! Can you believe it's been 7 weeks? (That's counting spring break.)

For the past 5 weeks, the spring sport athletes have been doing character development lessons as a way to stay engaged with teammates and coaches. This week's topic is Expectation vs Reality - it's very fitting for our current situation. This is a great message, not just for athletes, but for all of us: parents, students, teachers, community - everyone living through this time of not-knowing.

There's a short video - about 9 minutes - and then some written words to think about throughout the week. Have a look if you have the time and have a happy Thursday!

post_text:
The directors, cast, crew and musicians for this year‚Äôs spring musical, ‚ÄúMatilda‚Äù put in countless hours of hard work only to see it stopped four days short of our opening night. Although this has been such a disappointment for everyone involved, we all know that the COVID-19 pandemic has impacted the entire world. We are living in unprecedented times and every single area of our normal lives has been affected.

Unfortunately, we will not be able to perform this year. We appreciate the time, the talent, and the heart everyone gave. We all grew as performers as we sang, danced and acted to bring our wonderful ‚ÄúMatilda‚Äù to life. More importantly, we walked away from the show having experienced kindness, acceptance, compassion, tolerance, patience and love as part of the ‚ÄúMatilda‚Äù family.

As a department, we have decided to perform Matilda for the spring of 2021! Details will be given out at the beginning of next year regarding auditions, rehearsals and performance dates for next spring.

Pagosa Springs Community and Citizens,

Tonight, and every Friday until we return to our normal activity, the lights of Golden Peaks Stadium will be turned on as a symbol of hope - our hope to see you all again soon. Be strong and be safe as you work from home and know that you are never far from our hearts and minds. We are in this together!

During this time, we ask that you ‚ÄúBe the light‚Äù to others. Our challenge is for you to call and reach out to someone (a friend, loved one, family member) each and every day to be the light for them. Please encourage those people to be the light for someone else. TOGETHER, we will continue to shine through this adversity.

Please do not stop by the stadium, but feel free to drive by. Videos and pictures will be posted on social media.

Sincerely,
Pagosa Spring High School

post_text:
Congrats to our Skills USA students who competed at the regional competition in Durango on 2/14. 15 students are moving on to the state competition.

- The CSI B team of Andrew Boles, Trent Conner, and River Johnson took 1st place
- The CSI A team of Case Harris, James Hancey, and Isaiah Stene took 2nd place.
- The teamworks team of Alan Mendoza, Tad Hittle, and Ethan Hart (Trevor Moore and Tay Barker had wrestling tournament) took 2nd place.
- Mark Holladay took 1st place in computer programming.
- In carpentry, Timothy Hittle and Casey Beck earned 1st place and 2nd place respectively.
- Nathan Stahr took 3rd place in welding.
- Mason Blakemore earned 1st place in the welding sculpture competition.

Way to go Mr. Hessman and Mrs. Guilliams and all the students!

UPDATE- AUGUST 8th Physicals at the high school have been cancelled. Physicals are REQUIRED in order to practice Monday August 12th. Please make sure you have a current physical uploaded into Arbiter/PlanetHS before practice starts on Monday.

Planning on playing sports this year? Do you have a current physical in hand so that you can start fall practice on the 12th?

If your answer is "no", don't panic! We have set up the following dates with local providers to get your physical up to date.

At the high school:
August 5th: 9am-12pm (PSMC)
August 8th: 12pm-4pm (Alpine Medical)- CANCELLED

Can't make those dates? Physicals will also be offered at the middle school!
August 7th: 9am-12pm (Pagosa Medical Group)
August 12th: 9am-12pm (Alpine Medical)

Physicals will cost $25 but may be covered by your insurance. Forms are available online through the CHSAA Digital Platform (formerly Arbiter Athlete) and on the high school website. We will also have some printed out at the high school.

post_text:
2018-19 Cell Phone Policy

Please take a moment to review our cell phone policy.

All cell/smart phones should be powered off and placed in designated cell phone holder during class time.

Class time is defined as the tardy bell to the dismissal bell and includes the Advisory period. Students are welcome to use phones during passing and lunch periods, but not during classroom breaks.

Parents are encouraged to model proper use of electronic devices by not contacting students during scheduled class periods. In an emergency, parents/guardians should contact the office to get a message to their student.

Failure to comply with this policy may result in a student referral to the office and parent/guardian will be required to pick up the phone at the high school.

post_text:
Pagosa Springs High School is proud of the growth shown by the class of 2019. Since the State of Colorado implemented SAT as the standardized measurement of achievement at the high school level, this is the first class to have growth data from the PSAT to the SAT.

Through the hard work of the staff and students, they were above the state average growth percentiles in both Evidence Based Reading and Writing, and in Math. In Evidence Based Reading and Writing, they were in the 54th growth percentile, and in Math, they were in the 61st growth percentile.

While we are proud of the growth from the class of 2019, we recognize the need to improve and are committed to work to help all of our students be more successful on these measures of achievement.

In his recent trip to Guatemala, Vice President Mike Pence and his wife, Karen, visited the U.S. Army base, where they visited troops and took time for a photo shoot on June 28, 2018. Standing next to Mrs. Pence is Staff Sergeant Raul Palmer, a graduate of Pagosa Springs High School.

A former football and wrestling athlete, Raul was honored to stand close to the VP and his wife. He has served in the military since graduating from high school in 2005. Palmer and others in his troop received a commemorative coin from Second Lady Karen Pence.

"You never know where life is going to take you," says his father, Butch Palmer, who passed on the photo. ASD recognizes and salutes Raul for his many years serving his country.
